  "opinion": "As an 83-year-old retired hairdresser from Naples, I've seen many changes in the world, but social media is something I've never used myself, so my perspective comes from observing others and my own life experiences. Fake content on social media, from what I hear from my clients and friends, seems like a tangled mess that can spread faster than gossip in a small town. In my day, we dealt with rumors face-to-face, and you could usually tell the truth by looking someone in the eye, but online, it's all hidden behind screens, making it harder to trust what you see. To manage this, I believe in relying on good old-fashioned common sense and community. Just as I learned to trust my instincts when mixing hair colors or baking a cake—knowing when something feels off—people should pause and think before sharing or believing things online. Check sources, talk to real people you know, and don't let flashy headlines sway you. In Naples, we value family and tradition, and I think bringing that offline wisdom online can help. For example, when I bake, I follow trusted recipes passed down through generations; similarly, seek out reliable information from established sources. Since I'm retired and enjoy videogames as a hobby, I see how games can teach problem-solving, but they also show how easily things can be manipulated—a lesson for social media too. My Hindu beliefs emphasize truth and non-harm, so spreading fake content goes against that. Ultimately, dealing with fake content isn't just about technology; it's about fostering honesty and connection in our communities, whether online or off.",
